04700nam a22005775i 9780774851916DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748519167 a10.59962/97807748519162doi  a(DE-B1597)661933  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKF224.C69.P48 2003eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a3451 aPhillips, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMurdering Holiness :bThe Trials of Franz Creffield and George Mitchell /cRosemary Gartner, Jim Phillips. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b21 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCast of Principal Characters -- tIntroduction -- tThe Creffield Sect in Corvallis, 1903 -- tDriving Out the Sect -- t“Sensualist Practices Prescribed and Ordained as Coming from Heaven” -- tDisciplining the Sect -- tRevival and Revenge, January to May 1906 -- tSeattle Prepares for Trial, May and June 1906 -- tJustifiable Homicide and the Unwritten Law -- tThe Trial of George Mitchell, Part 1 -- tThe Trial of George Mitchell, Part 2 -- t“And the Evil That Men Do Lives After Them” -- tThe Law, Maud Creffield, and Esther Mitchell -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix: The Creffield Sect Membership -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMurdering Holiness explores the story of the "Holy Roller" sect led by Franz Creffield in the early years of the twentieth century. In the opening chapters, the authors introduce us to the community of Corvallis, Oregon, where Creffield, a charismatic, self-styled messiah, taught his followers to forsake their families and worldly possessions and to seek salvation through him. As his teachings became more extreme, the local community reacted: Creffield was tarred and feathered and his followers were incarcerated in the state asylum. Creffield himself was later imprisoned for adultery, but shortly after his release he revived the sect. This proved too much for some of the adherents' families, and in May 1906 George Mitchell, the brother of two women in the sect, pursued Creffield to Seattle and shot him dead. The authors take us into the courtroom for the trial that made headlines across North America, as Mitchell was acquitted of murder. Though the formal plea was insanity, the defence built its case on the "unwritten law" that justified killing to protect or avenge family honour. Based on court records and archival sources, this case study includes a detailed examination of the trial, the media's response to it, and the dramatic aftermath, and sheds light on the rise of ardent religion in the Pacific Northwest, the justice system in Seattle, and the role of the press in influencing public opinion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCultszOregon. 0aTrials (Adultery)zOregonzPortland. 0aTrials (Murder)zWashington (State)zSeattle. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aGartner, Rosemary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485191640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851916/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Pac